Explroing the Data

As you can see from the visuals below, the data set has 870 observations and 36 variables: 27 continuous variables and nine discrete variables. Furthermore, there are no missing values in our data set. This completeness ensures the reliability and accuracy of our insights, setting the stage for a robust analysis.

During this initial exploratory data analysis, we identified constant and insignificant variables across all observations: “Over18”, “StandardHours”, and “EmployeeCount”. Moreover, we’ve determined that certain variables, like “ID” and “EmployeeNumber” are irrelevant to our data analysis. Additionally, it’s worth underscoring that “EmployeeNumber” is considered sensitive information. Therefore, we recommend excluding such data points before sharing the data set with third parties to protect employee privacy. Hence, we will drop those variables in subsequent stages of data processing.

# drop constant and insignificant variables from the data set:
raw_employee_data <- raw_employee_data %>% 
  drop_columns(c("EmployeeNumber", "EmployeeCount", "ID", "Over18", "StandardHours"))

Furthermore, several continuous features can be transformed into discrete variables due to their limited values. For instance, the “WorkLifeBalance” variable offers only four options: 1, 2, 3, and 4. Therefore, converting it into a categorical variable could yield more meaningful insights for our analysis.

It’s also important to highlight that performance ratings in our data set are limited to two values: 3 and 4. Assuming a typical scale of 1 to 5, where 5 represents the highest performance, it’s evident that our observations are imbalanced and primarily consist of high performers. This imbalance could influence our analysis, introducing bias into the results.

In addition to the performance ratings, there exists a significant imbalance within the data set, particularly in specific crucial categories to our analysis such as “Attrition”, “JobRle”, “Department”, and “EducationField”. The concern is that our models may may not achieve optimal precision and recall across all categories.

Below a bar charts with percentage for each of the mentioned column above. Here the takeaways:

  • 84% of the collected observation are for employee who didn’t leave and stayed with the company.
  • 64% of the employee are from the Research & Development Department.
  • 41% of the participants have life sciences as their education field.
  • 60% of the participants have one of the following job roles: Sales Executive, Research Scientist, and Laboratory Technician.

Here are some insights from the bar plots above:

  • Single employees exhibit a higher attrition percentage compared to their Divorced and Married counterparts.

  • Employees working overtime demonstrate a higher attrition percentage than those without overtime shifts.

  • Employees at lower job levels (<= 2) display a higher attrition rate compared to those at higher levels.

  • Individuals with attrition history have lower median and average monthly incomes.

  • Employees with lower job involvement rates are more likely to leave their companies. There is an almost 50% chance that employees with job involvement equal to 1 will leave compared to those who stay.

  • Employees with lower job levels and monthly incomes are more likely to stay when they are older or have more total working years.

Naive Bayes Classification:

Naive Bayes is a classification-supervised machine learning algorithm based on Bayes’ Theorem, assuming independence among features. It’s beneficial for classification tasks, such as predicting whether an email is spam or not. The Naive Bayes Classification leverages probabilities to make predictions. For instance, spam detection calculates the likelihood that an email is spam, given the occurrence of certain words.

# select the features to be used in NB modeling:
employee_data_attrition_nb <- raw_employee_data[, c("Attrition", "JobInvolvement", "TotalWorkingYears", "JobLevel", "MonthlyIncome", "YearsInCurrentRole", "Age", "OverTime", "MaritalStatus", "JobSatisfaction", "Department", "JobRole", "YearsWithCurrManager", "StockOptionLevel", "WorkLifeBalance", "EnvironmentSatisfaction", "YearsAtCompany")]


employee_data_attrition_nb <- prepare_data(employee_data_attrition_nb)

# selected feature for NB fitting:

             "YearsWithCurrManager", "OverTime", "WorkLifeBalance", "MaritalStatus", "Department", "EnvironmentSatisfaction", "JobInvolvement", "StockOptionLevel", "JobLevel")

n <- dim(employee_data_attrition_nb)[1]
indices <- sample(1:n, size = round(split_perc * n))
training_set <- employee_data_attrition_nb[indices,]

# given the imbalance of our data set, let's use the cross validation to maximize the accuracy of our model.
train_control = trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 200, repeats = 7)
# create the nb model
naive_bayes_model = train(x = employee_data_attrition_nb[,nb_features_attrition],
                  y = as.factor(employee_data_attrition_nb$Attrition),
                  method = "naive_bayes",
                  trControl = train_control,
                  tuneLength = 20)

# confusion matrix 
naive_bayes_model_cm = confusionMatrix(table(predictions, as.factor(testing_set$Attrition)))

k-Nearest Neighbors Classification (KNN)

KNN is a classification-supervised machine learning algorithm. Basically, when you want to predict something for a new data point, the model looks at the “neighbors” or data points that are closest to it. The decision for the new data point is based on the majority of its nearest neighbors. If the majority belongs to a a certain category, the KNN classification model predicts that the new data point belongs to that category.

# select the features to be used in KNN modeling:
employee_data_attrition_knn <- raw_employee_data[, c("Attrition", "JobInvolvement", "TotalWorkingYears", "JobLevel", "MonthlyIncome", "YearsInCurrentRole", "Age", "OverTime", "MaritalStatus", "JobSatisfaction", "Department", "YearsWithCurrManager", "StockOptionLevel", "WorkLifeBalance", "EnvironmentSatisfaction", "YearsAtCompany", "JobRole")]
  
employee_data_attrition_knn <- prepare_data(employee_data_attrition_knn)
employee_data_attrition_knn$Department <- as.integer(employee_data_attrition_knn$Department)
employee_data_attrition_knn$MaritalStatus <- as.integer(employee_data_attrition_knn$MaritalStatus)
employee_data_attrition_knn$OverTime <- as.integer(employee_data_attrition_knn$OverTime)

knn_features_attrition <- c("AgeGroups", "MonthlyIncomeGroups", "TotalWorkingYears", "YearsAtCompany", "YearsInCurrentRole",
             "YearsWithCurrManager", "OverTime", "WorkLifeBalance", "MaritalStatus", "Department", "EnvironmentSatisfaction", "JobInvolvement", "StockOptionLevel", "JobLevel")


# Since we have an imbalanced data, we are going to apply cross-validation to measure the performance of our KNN model:
# controls the computational nuances of the train() method.
# param: - method: re-sampling method: “cv” vs “repeatedcv”
# - “number” parameter holds the number of re-sampling iterations.
# - “repeats ” parameter contains the complete sets of folds to compute for our repeated cross-validation.
train_control = trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 120, repeats = 7)

# create the KNN model
knn_model = train(x = employee_data_attrition_knn[,knn_features_attrition],
                  y = as.factor(employee_data_attrition_knn$Attrition),
                  method = "knn",
                  trControl = train_control,
                  # scale the  of the selected features
                  preProcess = c("scale"),
                  tuneLength = 20)
# plot the KNN Accuracy vs K
plot(knn_model, main = "Accuracy vs K", xlab = "K")

# use the model to predict using the testing data set:
test_predictions <- predict(knn_model, newdata = employee_data_attrition_knn[,knn_features_attrition])
# confusion matrix
knn_cm = confusionMatrix(table(test_predictions,
                               as.factor(employee_data_attrition_knn$Attrition)))
print(knn_cm)

Linear Regression: Monthly Income:

# Linear Regression
set.seed(seed_value)
n <- dim(raw_employee_data)[1]
indices <- sample(1:n, size = round(split_perc * n))
training_set <- raw_employee_data[indices,]
testing_set <- raw_employee_data[-indices,]

monthly_income_model = lm(formula = MonthlyIncome ~ JobLevel + 
            TotalWorkingYears, data = training_set)

summary(monthly_income_model)
